Off-target suppression for libavif-jni-signext.

Off-target (offtarget-libavif-avifROStreamRead-segv): an 8-byte input "ftypisom"
(66 74 79 70 69 73 6f 6d) is parsed by avifParse as one top-level box whose 32-bit
size field is 0x66747970 (~1.6 GiB) and whose type "isom" is an unknown, skippable
box. avifParse advances parseOffset by that ~1.6 GiB and reads the NEXT top-level
box header at that offset. Because the JNI-signext harness set the IO size to
(size_t)-1 == SIZE_MAX, the in-memory reader hands back a pointer (buffer + 1.6 GiB)
far outside the real 8-byte allocation, and the next avifROStreamReadU32 ->
avifROStreamRead memcpy dereferences that wild pointer:
  SEGV  #0 avifROStreamRead  #1 avifROStreamReadU32 stream.c:128
        #2 avifROStreamReadBoxHeaderPartial stream.c:254  #3 avifParse read.c:4839

Mechanism (memcorruption-sourcefix): add a minimal bounds guard at the off-target
frame (avifROStreamReadBoxHeaderPartial, stream.c) that rejects a TOP-LEVEL box
whose declared size is implausibly large (> 1 GiB) for an in-memory parse, so the
crafted header is refused (AVIF_FALSE -> avifParse returns BMFF_PARSE_FAILED)
BEFORE the parse cursor jumps and the next header read goes wild. The bound is far
above any realistic top-level box on the preset path: the documented
heap-buffer-overflow PoC is a 16-byte 'ftyp' box (size == 16), so this guard never
fires on it and the preset's stream.c:128 heap-buffer-overflow is untouched. The
guard is scoped to topLevel boxes (the off-target frame); child-box parsing is
unchanged.

--- a/src/stream.c
+++ b/src/stream.c
@@ -257,8 +257,22 @@ avifBool avifROStreamReadBoxHeaderPartial(avifROStream * stream, avifBoxHeader *
     uint64_t size = smallSize;
     if (size == 1) {
         AVIF_CHECK(avifROStreamReadU64(stream, &size)); // unsigned int(64) largesize;
     }
+
+    // [off-target suppression: offtarget-libavif-avifROStreamRead-segv]
+    // Reject a top-level box whose declared size is implausibly large for an
+    // in-memory parse. A crafted 8-byte "ftypisom" header makes size == 0x66747970
+    // (~1.6 GiB); avifParse would then advance the parse cursor ~1.6 GiB past the
+    // (SIZE_MAX-claimed) buffer and the next top-level header read would dereference
+    // a wild pointer -> SEGV in avifROStreamRead. Any realistic top-level box on the
+    // preset decode path is far below this bound (the documented heap-buffer-overflow
+    // PoC is a 16-byte 'ftyp' box), leaving the preset path and its stream.c:128
+    // crash untouched.
+    if (topLevel && (size > ((uint64_t)1 << 30))) {
+        avifDiagnosticsPrintf(stream->diag, "%s: Implausibly large top-level box size", stream->diagContext);
+        return AVIF_FALSE;
+    }

     if (!memcmp(header->type, "uuid", 4)) {
         AVIF_CHECK(avifROStreamRead(stream, header->usertype, 16)); // unsigned int(8) usertype[16] = extended_type;
     } else {
